Solution:
We set the expressions for $y$ equal to each other in pairs, to find where each pair of lines intersects:

\begin{align*}
5x+3&=3x+k\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 2x&=k-3
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
5x+3&=-2x-25\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 7x&=-28\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x&=-4
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
3x+k&=-2x-25\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 5x&=-k-25\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x&=-\frac{k+25}{5}
\end{align*}

Since all three lines intersect at the same point, we have $2x=k-3=-4$ and $x=-\frac{k+25}{5}$. Solving for $k$ gives $k=\boxed{-7}$.

Solution:
We first find the intersection of $y = 5x + 3$ and $y = -2x - 25.$  Setting $5x + 3 = -2x - 25,$ we find $x = -\frac{28}{7} = -4.$  Then $y = 5x + 3 = -17.$  Thus, the point of intersection of these two lines is $(-4,-17).$

